data.text: In this paper, comprehensive pulsar-based Guidance, Navigation and Control (GNC) system is designed and applied to satellites formation flying. The complete autonomy of the X-ray pulsar navigation technology provides both absolute and relative positioning information for spacecraft in or even beyond the solar system, and provides an interesting alternative solution to classical navigation techniques such as Global Navigation Satellite System (GNSS). The navigation measurements are studied using a relative time of arrival (RTOA) estimating method, which takes advantage of the noise-filtered pulsar profiles in the cross-correlation estimator to achieve robustness. An adaptive Kalman filter is exploited to minimise the effect of processing noises caused by the primary satellite. A linear Quadratic Gaussian regulator is then applied to control the formation. To different configurations are studied in in HEO. Simulation results show that the designed GNC algorithms can fulfill the required accuracy of XXXXX.

data.text: The complete autonomy of the X-ray pulsar navigation technology provides both absolute and relative positioning information for spacecraft in or even beyond the solar system. Thus, a comprehensive pulsar-based Guidance Navigation, and Control (GNC) system is first designed and applied to satellite formation flying missions. The navigation measurements are studied by the proposed relative time of arrival (RTOA) estimating method, which utilizes the noise-filtered pulsar profiles in the Cross-Correlation estimator to achieve the robustness. Furthermore, the architecture and algorithms of the presented pulsar-based GNC system are developed. The adaptive Kalman filter is exploited to reduce the effect of processing noises caused by the primary satellite. The linear Quadratic Gaussian controller is applied to accomplish the forming up and the formation-keeping of two formation configurations in high Earth orbits (HEOs).
